ce:section.ce:para:
Fig. 10
 depicts a possible photocatalytic pathway of a metal-free photocatalyst of N-GQDs in the dye solution. Because N-GQDS with a larger negative surface can effectively attract cationic dye molecules (Rh B, MB) on its surface, many dye molecules can interact with the photocatalyst, resulting in high photocatalytic degradation efficiency under visible light illumination. Photoinduced electrons as well as holes are separated in the valence band of the N-GQDS surface, and these electrons and holes may be essential to dye molecule degradation. The photoexcited electrons get excited to the conductance band (CB) from the valence band [47,48]. Meanwhile, some electrons are trapped by defects in the surface, hindering the recombination of e−/h + pairs, while others are taken by dissolved oxygen and create superoxide radicals (•O
   2
) [13]. Photosensitized holes react with water to generate hydroxyl radicals (•OH) [49] or interact directly with dye molecules to generate organic radicals. The active oxygen species (•O
   2
) and hydroxyl radicals interact with dye molecules and degrade the dye molecules at the same time.
